WEBVTT

00:01.700 --> 00:11.840
The tapes are on. Okay, so you wrote the Essex book. So yeah, could you kind of
give us a general history of those, and then I'll hit on the specifics that you

00:11.840 --> 00:24.500
don't cover. Well, in the first place, I'd moved from Syracuse, New York, to Los
Angeles District in 1965.

00:27.740 --> 00:40.400
And at that time, I was working as a tech writer for the space defense industry.
And of course, I was writing on the side. I built up a good backlog of science

00:40.400 --> 00:54.700
fiction novels and short stories. But I hadn't become a full-time writer. Well,
in 1969, a month before the first moon landing, NASA had its funds cut way back,

00:54.820 --> 01:05.960
and thousands of people working in the space industry were laid off, including
myself. So I couldn't get a job there for a while, and finally I got one, and I

01:05.960 --> 01:20.920
said, I want to go into full-time writing, and I did. Well, shortly thereafter,
though I had a lot of money coming in from my book publishers, I couldn't get it

01:20.920 --> 01:33.860
out of them. I guess they were going through one of those slumps where they were
reluctant to let loose funds, and I needed some money. Well, at that time, I was

01:33.860 --> 01:48.420
approached by a fellow named Brian Kirby, who was a science fiction fan, but he
also was an editor for a pornographic book publishing outfit, I think called

01:48.420 --> 02:03.740
American Art Agency. And he was starting a new line called Essex House. Although
Brian had been an editor for some time in the porno field, he was pretty much

02:03.740 --> 02:14.820
disgusted with the books because, one, the writing level was very low, and there
wasn't any characterization or plot or motivation, and very little imagination.

02:14.820 --> 02:25.280
And he wanted to raise the literary level of the porno books, I mean, at least
the ones in the new line Essex House. He also loved science fiction, so he

02:25.280 --> 02:38.040
approached a number of science fiction authors, and asked them if they'd be
interested. At that time, 1969, I'd never even read one of those books, unless

02:38.040 --> 02:49.720
you count Henry Miller as a porno writer, and I don't. And I said, yeah, I'm a
writer, I'd like to try anything. I'll even write romances if I have to.

02:53.380 --> 03:06.140
So he said there would be no taboos or guidelines. Normally, in the porno books,
they have guidelines, and that you have to have a sex scene every four or five,

03:06.440 --> 03:24.560
six pages. He said you can write it exactly the way you want to. So I decided
that I would write a satirical pastiche on my two heroes, one Tarzan and one the

03:24.560 --> 03:36.540
Hero of Pope magazine series, which started in the 30s, called Doc Savage. Doc
Savage is pretty well known even now, because Bantam started reprinting his

03:36.540 --> 03:55.540
books in 1965. So I wrote that, and I had a lot of fun with it. And it went out
where, I didn't know. And then I wrote a book called The Image of the Beast,

03:55.940 --> 04:06.020
which was sort of a satire on gothics and also on private eye novels, and
incidentally, it was a satire on porno books, too.

04:08.800 --> 04:19.560
So that went out, and then I wrote a sequel called Blown, a sequel to The Image
of the Beast. And about that time, I got kind of tired. I guess even if you have

04:19.560 --> 04:31.120
a vivid imagination, there's only so much that you can do with books that are
basically sexual situations. And though I gave it my best, I had

04:31.120 --> 04:44.160
characterization and humor and plot and motivation and all that, I got tired of
it, so I ceased writing for them. And about that time, my publishers started

04:44.160 --> 04:56.460
coming through with all the money they'd owed me anyway. Now, what happened was
that the people who ran the American Art Agency knew nothing whatsoever about

04:56.460 --> 05:07.540
science fiction. And all they knew was porno books. So they made the very bad
mistake of sending all these science fiction books, which I and some other

05:07.540 --> 05:21.500
science fiction readers had written, to the porno bookshops, not to the
general bookstores. And as a result, they didn't sell well, because the usual

05:21.500 --> 05:30.280
porno customer wasn't interested in them. And by the time that the science
fiction people heard that these books were available, the American Art Agency

05:30.280 --> 05:42.020
had already decided to cancel Ethics House. It wasn't a financial go for them,
but it was their own fault. Well, I don't know how many of these three books

05:42.020 --> 05:56.900
that I wrote were printed. I do know that at one time I was told there were
hundreds or maybe even thousands in a warehouse in Los Angeles. But I've never

05:56.900 --> 06:06.400
been able to find out if they're still there or what, because the American Art
Agency closed up a couple of years ago. And I've had no success in getting a

06:06.400 --> 06:18.680
hold of the person who's handling the estate. Is that enough, or do you want to
ask me questions? No, that sounds good. Does it surprise you that the books are

06:18.680 --> 06:29.660
now considered to be top-end collector's items in command? Oh, I've seen them
anywhere from $75 to $150 a piece. Did that ever enter your mind? Well, it never

06:29.660 --> 06:39.320
entered my mind at the time I wrote them. If I had, I would have kept the copies
that Brian Kirby gave me. As it was, I just passed them out to friends here and

06:39.320 --> 06:51.020
there. And as a result, I only have about one or two samples of each of them. If
I'd known what was going to happen, I would have purchased three or four boxfuls

06:51.020 --> 07:01.760
myself. When word got around, of course, collectors being what they are, they
look for rare and unusual books, and they had difficulty finding them. So, of

07:01.760 --> 07:14.180
course, the price went up right away, and it's been going up steadily since
then. Another aspect of that was that after the American Art Agency folded, I

07:14.180 --> 07:25.460
got my rights back to the books, and then I tried to sell them to a national
publisher. But I didn't have any success for ten years. Nobody would touch them.

07:26.320 --> 07:43.780
And then finally, Playboy Press decided to publish them, and Granada in England
decided that they would do it. Also another publisher, I forget their name. The

07:43.780 --> 07:58.560
English publishers were taking a chance because they were afraid they would be
bought to court as it happened. They got by okay. And now, of course, why the

07:58.560 --> 08:12.200
books are, in comparison with other books dealing with sex, they're not, well, I
wouldn't exactly call them innocuous, but their

08:12.200 --> 08:26.240
far-ranging sexual ideas are not so much, they can't be accepted now. Back in 69
and 70, when I wrote them, my national publisher is just afraid to pick a chance

08:26.240 --> 08:38.140
with them. I always thought that the Doc Caliban character on the front of A
Feast Unknown looked kind of like you. The hair and the general facial features,

08:38.300 --> 08:52.340
is that just coincidence? Well, it probably is, unless Brian Kirby described me
to the artist, which he could have done. I never thought about it told truth.

08:52.340 --> 09:10.740
It's kind of a last gasp there. Now, you wrote, Lord of the Trees and the Mad
Goblin are clean sequels to A Feast Unknown. And did you just kind of do those

09:10.740 --> 09:23.480
to, or just to keep up with the fun, the pastiche type writing? Yeah, that was
the main thing. The thing was, of course, in the Feast Unknown, my two heroes,

09:23.740 --> 09:28.680
Doc Caliban and Lord Gribardsun,

09:30.840 --> 09:41.640
were engaged in eliminating this ancient evil Council of Nine. And they'd only
knocked off a few in the first book, so I wanted to continue their adventures,

09:41.700 --> 09:51.180
which I did in the Mad Goblin and the Lord of the Trees. And they succeeded in
eliminating a few more of the Council of Nine. However, there are still some

09:51.180 --> 10:02.640
left, so I plan on writing at least one sequel to those and finishing up the
job. Although I don't know when I'm going to do it. You know, actually, I have

10:02.640 --> 10:15.360
about 15 theories going, none of which I've ever finished. Well, when I was
young and went to a psychologist while I was attending the University of

10:15.360 --> 10:20.660
Missouri, he commented that I had terrible difficulty in finishing anything.

10:23.700 --> 10:33.700
So we'll look forward to seeing some more of those then. Well, I hope so. I had
a lot of fun writing them. And I didn't continue the sexual theme in them. In

10:33.700 --> 10:45.660
the first place, I think I exhausted them in the first two books. In the second
place, it's difficult to get publishers to accept them if you do have that theme

10:45.660 --> 10:58.280
there. A less obvious sequel to me was Traitor to the Living as a sequel to
Blown. It seems like it was a little more subtle there that that might be a

10:58.280 --> 11:07.740
sequel. Is it a sequel? Can it be considered a sequel? Oh, yeah, it's a sequel.
I think some of the readers weren't aware of it at the time. Actually, that's

11:07.740 --> 11:11.160
why it opened for another sequel, too, you know. Good. I enjoyed it.

11:14.600 --> 11:27.040
Okay, what about Love Song, then? That was Brandon House. Are they connected
with Essex House, or how did that come about? Well, I guess I was... Yeah, okay.

11:27.440 --> 11:40.640
I wrote that about the time I decided I wasn't going to do it anymore, but I
already had a contract. So I wrote it. It was not science fiction. It sounded

11:40.640 --> 11:51.840
like a gothic, but it had a rational explanation at the end. That's even a rarer
book than The Feast Unknown, Image of the Beast, and Blown. So I've noticed.

11:52.060 --> 12:05.140
Very difficult to get a hold of. So, again, I only have one copy. Now, it has
not been reprinted anywhere, has it? No. I wanted to write in to whoever was

12:05.140 --> 12:14.600
handling the estate and get their rights back. Unfortunately, I can't find him.
This wasn't Brian Kirby and Essex House, that Brandon House is something

12:14.600 --> 12:27.860
different? It was... Brandon House was a line that had existed before Essex
