books, wrote a couple. And I'd always had a desire, ever since I was young, to
be a writer, and I'd always wanted to write an Oz book. But I didn't get around

19:47.320 --> 20:01.820
to it until I was 64 years old. Now, of course, the book that I would write when
I'm 64 is quite different from the one that I would write if I were 10 or 11. So

20:01.820 --> 20:06.800
I'm waiting to hear the reaction from the members of the International Wizard of
Oz Club.

20:09.760 --> 20:21.720
Because this, as you know, assumes that only the first Oz book, The Wonderful
Wizard of Oz, is true. And that's all the rest are fiction. And then it

20:21.720 --> 20:33.180
approaches Oz from a science fictional viewpoint. That is, it could have existed
if it did, then you have to explain how a scarecrow could be animated and

20:33.180 --> 20:48.860
sentient and talk. What would happen if animals could talk? How do you account
for the 10 woodman's piecemeal method of being reconstructed out of 10? and

20:48.860 --> 20:56.580
explain magic and explain magic and all that sort of stuff from just where Oz
was. I had a lot of fun doing it, but I also had to do an awful lot of research

20:58.260 --> 21:05.740
because it took place in 1923 and I had to read all about what was happening in
America at that time.

21:09.660 --> 21:19.920
and I've been a World War I and early aviation buff and I have a considerable
library on that, but I still had to look up a lot of things on the Jennings and

21:19.920 --> 21:33.720
on the machine guns and the BARs of that period and army organization, politics,
and all that sort of thing. plus, of course, the agonizing task of being able to

21:33.720 --> 21:44.780
explain in a rational manner just how the land of Oz could exist and how all
these beings could exist in it. Also, there's something you may not have

21:44.780 --> 22:00.900
noticed. There's a character in there called Sharts the Shirtless. Okay. And he
actually is sort of a wild Doc Savage. If you were acquainted with the first Doc

22:00.900 --> 22:18.120
Savage magazine that came out, you would see that his shirt was torn to shreds.
And the, when the 1965 reissues by Bantam came out, the artist, what was his

22:18.120 --> 22:33.000
name? Hmm. I can't remember it right off right hand. But anyway, he continued
that torn shirt motif. So, Sharts, the shirtless, is sort of an Ozziean takeoff

22:33.000 --> 22:48.540
on Doc Savage. Plus the fact that his rare, his companion, the rare beast logo,
is sort of a takeoff on Doc Savage's apish buddy, Monk Mayfair. It doesn't

22:48.540 --> 22:59.720
matter to the reader whether he knows that or not, but if he does know it, it
