25:00.380 --> 25:08.080
the main thing was, of course, obviously, the later books were fiction. I mean,
there were so many contradictions and changes.

25:12.800 --> 25:21.860
Why was Oz so popular? I guess it was almost an instant success and a
continuance, and it still is popular. Why do you think that those books are so

25:21.860 --> 25:24.420
popular? Well,

25:28.040 --> 25:43.900
of course, there were many books written back in 1900 and afterwards about
foreign lands or fairy lands, but what Baum did was to create a magnificent

25:43.900 --> 25:57.880
quest, and what you have Dorothy looking for a way of getting home, the cowardly
lion, wanting courage, tin woodmen running a heart, and a scarecrow running

25:57.880 --> 26:09.920
brain. Now, the thing is, they all thought that the wonderful Wizard of Oz could
give it to them. Well, he told them he would, but he put them through a series

26:09.920 --> 26:22.880
of trials. You know, first they had to go out and kill the wicked witch of the
West, and I forget offhand what the other quest was. But the point was that they

26:22.880 --> 26:24.520
had all these qualities that they wanted.

26:27.840 --> 26:38.220
The scarecrow was ignorant, but he was intelligent, and the tin woodmen had a
very tender heart, even if he didn't have a heart inside that tin body. And the

26:38.220 --> 26:53.060
carly lion was like all of us. He'd get scared, but he was able to overcome his
fear. But they needed some magical reassurance, and finally when they exposed

26:53.060 --> 27:06.820
the Wizard of Oz as a humbug, he still concocted devices, physical devices,
which were symbols of what they wanted. You know, he had the cowardly lion drink

27:06.820 --> 27:16.140
a pot of courage. Somebody had suggested it was probably Dutch courage. And he
made a heart out of velvet

27:17.060 --> 27:20.260
filled with sawdust and put it inside the tin woodman's body.

27:24.840 --> 27:35.520
he stuck, oh, okay. He put bran inside the scarecrow's head, and then he put
needles in them, and he said his head was brand new now, and it was sharp,

27:36.460 --> 27:46.600
needle sharp, of course. Baum was great for fun. And having these physical
evidence of things they wanted, they proceeded to be very happy, although they'd

27:46.600 --> 27:58.820
had these qualities all this time. And I think that moral there, that wonderful
quest that found both for them,

28:02.000 --> 28:11.120
was something that appealed to the hearts of all the kids, and of course adults
too. And then, of course, Dorothy had had the means of getting home all the

28:11.120 --> 28:24.920
time, because when the Wicked Witch of the East was crushed by her house,
dropping out of the cyclone, she put on the silver slippers of the witch, and

28:24.920 --> 28:33.980
wore them all through her adventure, not knowing that all she had to do was wish
to be back in Kansas, and she could go home. It wasn't until Glinda the Good, at

28:33.980 --> 28:44.620
the end of the book, told her that her shoes could do it, that Dorothy realized
that all this time, she could have gone home a few minutes after she got into

28:44.620 --> 28:54.340
odds if she wanted to. In other words, Baum was saying, well, look, look around
you, maybe you have the means for success or escape around you, you don't have

28:54.340 --> 29:05.780
to find some magical means. Although, of course, the silver slippers were
magical. Well, anyway, that's my explanation of the popularity of the book. And,

29:05.800 --> 29:14.020
of course, there are millions who, I suppose, never read the book, who know
about Oz through the movie.

